Text: Last week felt like an avalanche as I, like everyone else, rushed to finish the last few (or many) pieces of our deliverables.
Not to mention the fact that we're already half way onto the program, and that within two weeks we should try to look job/internship-ready.
Still, last week has been quite productive.
I and Koko managed to implement a smart list for our row and column filters, and then deployed our codes onto Google Colab.
Eric can now upload a file and process it by just pressing the run button.
Of course, if he does just a bit more than that, the whole thing would probably crash.
On my own, I also revised some helper functions and added a dozen of unit tests after discovering some breaking bugs along the way.

Comp150's emphasis on test-driven-development turns out to be extremely helpful in this regard, and Python's doc-test has been a pleasure to work with, as opposed to Node where I feel like there's less incentive and a bit of a learning curve.
That said, this whole process of debugging did feel a bit slow and painful, and I think I've experienced firsthand the trade-off of using dynamically typed languages.
I've also discovered that I really enjoyed writing tests and coding in a test-driven way.

As such, I really want to further develop my test-writing skills and practice TDD more in project 3, the second of which can take the form of using Typescript, Python's type-hint, or learning a statically-typed server-side language like Go.
I've also heard QA/Test Automation being thrown around, so I'm keen to find out more about it and how it fits into a typical workflow.
Team-wise, it turned out I shouldn't have worried too much over Kuku's take on things.
My teammates have fortunately been supportive as well, and I felt like we've been much more open to each other compared to the first 2 weeks.
On Friday, I and Bibi shared and discussed what we did well and could've done better regarding our teamwork skills.
It was great hearing him opening up about how his project work in Polytech shaped his approach to team-coding and communication in general.
It turns out we both like the sense of total control over our codes, and this project has gently (I hope) alerted us to the reality of most IT teams.
In addition, I personally think that this reluctance speaks to another aspect of my teamwork skills that has somewhat been improved.
It indicates that I need to value and believe in my teammates more and realize that there's more than just the deliverables.
A team where each person feels supported and trusted should rank among the top agenda as well.

It's ironic that as a former teacher I am supposed to embrace this inclusive mentality, but I guess it shows how I need to take a step back from all the self-imposed and real-time pressure, to appreciate the people who make all these projects possible in the first place.
For this week, I'm hoping to finish the final report on time and contribute to the team's final presentation.
On the technical side, the goal is to finish migrating the database, server, and pipeline to a new Gmail account and to write up some basic documentation.
All in all, there's considerable overlap among these so I'm confident I and my team can carry it through by the end of this week.
Overall
